Task 1: Capture DNS Traffic with tcpdump
Step 1.1: Identify Network Interface
Check available network interfaces:

ip addr show
Note your primary interface (typically eth0 or ens33).

Step 1.2: Capture DNS Traffic
Start capturing DNS traffic on port 53:

sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -n port 53
Flags explained:

-i eth0: Specify interface
-n: Skip hostname resolution
port 53: Filter DNS traffic only
Step 1.3: Generate Test Traffic
Open a new terminal and create DNS queries:

nslookup google.com
nslookup github.com
nslookup amazon.com
Step 1.4: Save Capture to File
Capture DNS traffic to a pcap file for analysis:

sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -n -w dns_capture.pcap port 53
Let it run for 2-3 minutes while generating queries. Press Ctrl+C to stop.

Step 1.5: Read Captured Traffic
View the captured packets:

sudo tcpdump -r dns_capture.pcap -n
For verbose output:

sudo tcpdump -r dns_capture.pcap -n -v
